Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.273 --> 00:00:03.564
GUS GOSTYLA: Welcome, everyone.

00:00:03.564 --> 00:00:05.579
They put us back in the
corner, because they

00:00:05.579 --> 00:00:06.870
knew we were the loose cannons.

00:00:06.870 --> 00:00:09.130
So we're way in the back.

00:00:09.130 --> 00:00:11.110
Hope you're woken
up from your lunch.

00:00:11.110 --> 00:00:11.930
Welcome, everyone.

00:00:11.930 --> 00:00:12.930
Thanks for coming today.

00:00:12.930 --> 00:00:15.900
I'm Gus Gostyla, and I
look after cultivating

00:00:15.900 --> 00:00:19.060
our relationships with the
venture capital and startup

00:00:19.060 --> 00:00:22.920
community on behalf of
Google and Android, Google

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:24.030
Play and Android.

00:00:24.030 --> 00:00:26.720
And my colleague
is Ellie Powers,

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:29.960
who will take the second half,
who leads our developer product

00:00:29.960 --> 00:00:30.984
team here.

00:00:30.984 --> 00:00:32.900
The two of us have been
spending a lot of time

00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:34.760
with startups this year.

00:00:34.760 --> 00:00:38.595
So I'd like to ask how many
people work at startups

00:00:38.595 --> 00:00:39.470
who are in the crowd.

00:00:39.470 --> 00:00:41.330
Get a show of hands.

00:00:41.330 --> 00:00:41.840
Awesome.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:45.230
Like, it's less than 100
people kind of companies.

00:00:45.230 --> 00:00:46.420
That's great.

00:00:46.420 --> 00:00:49.360
You're in the right place.

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:55.460
So we're here to talk
to you about how many of

00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:57.220
you are succeeding
on Google Play,

00:00:57.220 --> 00:00:59.720
and why more and more
are launching on Android

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:01.500
and SIM shipping your apps.

00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:03.970
And to start, you could say
this is a bit of a passion

00:01:03.970 --> 00:01:05.800
area for me personally.

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:08.690
I spent a good chunk of my
career at mobile startups.

00:01:08.690 --> 00:01:13.520
Most recently ones like
Inkling and Flipboard.

00:01:13.520 --> 00:01:15.720
And now I get to sit on
the other side of the fence

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:17.680
where my team is
focused exclusively

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:22.520
on helping startups
succeed and making it

00:01:22.520 --> 00:01:25.170
feel like less of a black art.

00:01:25.170 --> 00:01:30.482
So while the team is new,
in just the last few months

00:01:30.482 --> 00:01:32.440
it's already become
obvious to Ellie and myself

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:33.940
that there are some
recurring themes

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:37.430
we hear from startups
that come to Android.

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:42.010
And so we'd like to discuss
those with you here.

00:01:42.010 --> 00:01:43.840
Specifically, we broke
the recurring themes

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:45.381
down into three
buckets that we would

00:01:45.381 --> 00:01:49.495
label as follows-- Reach, the
Next Billion, and Iteration.

00:01:49.495 --> 00:01:50.870
And we'll spend
our time drilling

00:01:50.870 --> 00:01:54.670
down on how to get
the most out of those.

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:56.330
And we'll also share
three case studies

00:01:56.330 --> 00:01:59.860
of startups who are really
representing those themes well

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:03.520
and demonstrating best
practices in these areas.

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:06.220
So let's get started with
Reach and the First Billion

00:02:06.220 --> 00:02:09.080
before we go on to
the Next Billion.

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:11.184
You've probably heard
of Benedict Evans

00:02:11.184 --> 00:02:12.350
over at Andreessen Horowitz.

00:02:12.350 --> 00:02:16.770
He's one of my personal
favorite mobile pundits

00:02:16.770 --> 00:02:18.530
in the mobile tech world.

00:02:18.530 --> 00:02:22.100
And he's prolific with his
dispatches on subject of mobile

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:23.350
eating the world.

00:02:23.350 --> 00:02:26.300
So a few months ago
he said this-- mobile

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:29.080
is the first universal
tech product.

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:32.550
And he was referring to the
data on the following slide.

00:02:32.550 --> 00:02:34.050
And he points out
some projections

00:02:34.050 --> 00:02:35.560
from various
sources, specifically

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:39.660
global population on the left
of nearly 8 billion people

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:41.180
projected in 2020.

00:02:41.180 --> 00:02:46.480
And the population of people
over 16 years old at 6 billion.

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:49.890
And finally, smartphones
projected at 5 billion in 2020,

00:02:49.890 --> 00:02:52.280
way further on the left.

00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:56.510
And the expected growth
you can see in purple

00:02:56.510 --> 00:02:58.080
between 2015 and 2020.

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:01.740
His point is, and my
point is, that smartphones

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:05.180
are starting to get close
to nearly reaching everyone

00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:06.930
on the planet.

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:08.520
And that's kind of a big deal.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:11.490
It's pretty profound
and non-trivial when

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:13.220
you consider how
little effort is

00:03:13.220 --> 00:03:15.590
required to make
and sell products

00:03:15.590 --> 00:03:19.017
that reach nearly everyone.

00:03:19.017 --> 00:03:20.850
And there's never really
been a similar kind

00:03:20.850 --> 00:03:22.940
of product or platform.

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:27.190
Sure, Coca-Cola, bicycles, and
refrigerators are neat too,

00:03:27.190 --> 00:03:28.840
and they have great reach.

00:03:28.840 --> 00:03:32.090
But they're not quite the
same democratizing platforms

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:35.050
for allowing the world
to communicate, transact,

00:03:35.050 --> 00:03:39.484
and disseminate information
in quite the same way.

00:03:39.484 --> 00:03:40.900
So now when we
think about Android

00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:44.210
and how it factors into
that global reach, last year

00:03:44.210 --> 00:03:47.120
Android crossed a
pretty huge threshold

00:03:47.120 --> 00:03:49.840
with over a billion devices
shipped around the world.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:54.000
And now you can see us logging
in 1.4 billion 30-day actives.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.450
And we've seen 1.5
million Android devices

00:03:56.450 --> 00:03:57.920
being activated daily.

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:01.400
And the continued platform
momentum of 400 OEMs

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:04.770
and 500 operators
on the platform.

00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:07.260
It's pretty incredible
that Play was launched just

00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:08.760
over four years ago.

00:04:08.760 --> 00:04:11.200
While Android is expanding
the footprint of device

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:13.700
availability, Play is helping
developers build businesses

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:15.020
across the globe.

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:18.829
And it's growing pretty
fast in its own right.

00:04:18.829 --> 00:04:21.160
Way back when I
was in your shoes,

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:23.300
back at mobile app startups
and Android was just

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:26.370
getting started, in the echo
chamber here in the Valley

00:04:26.370 --> 00:04:29.160
it was still kind of
fashionable to pick on Android

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:33.160
and say it lacked billion
dollar startup success stories.

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:34.930
And then something
funny happened.

00:04:34.930 --> 00:04:38.680
Companies like WhatsApp and
Uber, Line King, Flipkart,

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:42.380
Spotify, Supercell
started sprouting up

00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:45.590
in these insane
growth trajectories,

00:04:45.590 --> 00:04:50.290
and have become massive global
brands in their own right.

00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:52.130
Ask any of those
companies now if Android

00:04:52.130 --> 00:04:53.421
is important to their business.

00:04:53.421 --> 00:04:54.540
And I think they'll agree.

00:04:54.540 --> 00:04:57.460
My point is this-- my experience
at startups made it clear

00:04:57.460 --> 00:04:59.790
that a founder's
job is fundamentally

00:04:59.790 --> 00:05:02.220
to challenge the
status quo thinking,

00:05:02.220 --> 00:05:04.880
and observe what is
changing around you.

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:08.160
Ask yourself what you know
to be true in the future,

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:11.536
and execute relentlessly
on your vision.

00:05:11.536 --> 00:05:12.910
So in that light,
I'd ask you all

00:05:12.910 --> 00:05:14.660
to take a hard look
at Android when you're

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:16.260
getting started
on your next idea,

00:05:16.260 --> 00:05:18.730
and consider how Reach
might factor heavily

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:20.334
in your startup's
growth objectives.

00:05:20.334 --> 00:05:22.750
Of course, many of you have
already asked these questions.

00:05:22.750 --> 00:05:24.580
And that's why
you're here today.

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:27.120
And so keep plugging
away on Android.

00:05:27.120 --> 00:05:29.320
That's awesome.

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:32.150
Once you've made your
Android platform decision,

00:05:32.150 --> 00:05:34.870
what should you do next to
realize the full benefits

00:05:34.870 --> 00:05:35.990
of smartphone reach?

00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:39.510
Well, there's a couple things
you need to know to get there.

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:42.520
In our experience, these
are the first few things

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:44.380
you should be thinking about.

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:45.520
Building for reach.

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:47.290
So let's begin with material.

00:05:47.290 --> 00:05:49.310
The last session was
all about material.

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:51.960
And there was code on
slides and all that stuff.

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:54.280
We're not going to
do that here today.

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:56.310
But I did want to
point this one out,

00:05:56.310 --> 00:05:58.310
because maybe it's not
immediately obvious,

00:05:58.310 --> 00:06:00.870
but material has been
crucial for startups

00:06:00.870 --> 00:06:03.160
trying to attain reach.

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:06.140
And in that material offers
one universal language

00:06:06.140 --> 00:06:09.590
for navigation and interaction
that is becoming second nature

00:06:09.590 --> 00:06:10.604
for Android users.

00:06:10.604 --> 00:06:12.520
And I myself, having
come from those startups,

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:14.436
I was skeptical about
material when they first

00:06:14.436 --> 00:06:17.760
told me about it, and
felt like our apps should

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:19.850
look the same across all
platforms and that kind

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:22.650
of thing.

00:06:22.650 --> 00:06:26.770
But basically what I've learned
is that by using material,

00:06:26.770 --> 00:06:28.970
you already have
a huge head start

00:06:28.970 --> 00:06:31.210
on using a design that
most of those billion

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:35.050
plus users around the
world already understand,

00:06:35.050 --> 00:06:38.200
and in a way that is so
prevalent that it's now

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:41.274
making its way onto
other platforms, as well.

00:06:41.274 --> 00:06:42.690
As a result,
developers are seeing

00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:45.080
leaps in engagement
and conversion rates

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:47.540
across the board when
they implement it.

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:50.300
And you can see some of
the great examples here.

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:53.010
Apps like Fablic,
Musicmatch, Trello

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:57.330
seeing some notable increases
in time and activity

00:06:57.330 --> 00:06:59.080
in their apps.

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:01.150
And so yes, material is cool.

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:02.760
But also think from
the business side

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:10.180
about it being this common
language that everybody gets.

00:07:10.180 --> 00:07:14.727
While startups told us material
design was cool when we first

00:07:14.727 --> 00:07:17.060
announced it, you also told
us that it was a little hard

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:19.940
to know where to get
started, and that you

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:23.420
wanted more resources to make
building material apps easier.

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:24.656
And so we totally heard you.

00:07:24.656 --> 00:07:26.030
And over the past
few years we've

00:07:26.030 --> 00:07:27.738
been rolling out a
bunch of new resources

00:07:27.738 --> 00:07:30.540
that you can find at
design.google.com.

00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:33.050
I won't go into all the
details of all these things

00:07:33.050 --> 00:07:36.330
here, given the last
presentation probably

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:38.580
went into great depth there.

00:07:38.580 --> 00:07:43.999
But that's a hub you can
go find resources from.

00:07:43.999 --> 00:07:45.540
Another thing a lot
of startups worry

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:47.914
about when they're approaching
Android for the first time

00:07:47.914 --> 00:07:49.600
is device compatibility.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:52.510
Last year at Google I/O we
announced Cloud Test lab

00:07:52.510 --> 00:07:53.030
and Beta.

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:55.250
And this year we're taking
the training wheels off

00:07:55.250 --> 00:07:56.990
and moving it into Firebase.

00:07:56.990 --> 00:07:59.490
And as you'd expect,
Firebase test lab

00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:01.570
is integrated with
many different tools.

00:08:01.570 --> 00:08:04.025
So you can bring it into
your workflow easily.

00:08:04.025 --> 00:08:05.650
I'm sure some of you
have probably been

00:08:05.650 --> 00:08:08.350
to other sessions
on Firebase already.

00:08:08.350 --> 00:08:11.230
And I would urge
you as a startup

00:08:11.230 --> 00:08:14.500
to really think about this
platform, because it's

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:17.920
got so many different
things in it

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:20.360
wrapped up into
one great package,

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:22.720
whereas companies that
are a little further along

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:24.890
tend to specialize in
the tools they use.

00:08:24.890 --> 00:08:28.560
So Firebase is especially
well-suited to startups

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:30.870
who are just figuring it out.

00:08:30.870 --> 00:08:34.024
In Google Play, all
alpha and beta apps

00:08:34.024 --> 00:08:36.190
are tested against a
representative range of devices

00:08:36.190 --> 00:08:37.840
of profiles in the cloud.

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:40.080
This test is
completely automated.

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:42.130
So you don't need to
write test scripts.

00:08:42.130 --> 00:08:44.540
You can detect where there
are any obvious issues

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:48.580
on these devices before rolling
out your app to all users.

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:51.560
And you can now enable this
from within the dev console.

00:08:51.560 --> 00:08:54.190
The best part of the
base level of this

00:08:54.190 --> 00:08:59.430
is that it's totally
free, which is awesome.

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:02.750
After trying the pre-launch
report in the death console,

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:04.560
the next thing
developers say they

00:09:04.560 --> 00:09:07.790
want is to run exactly
the set of tasks they want

00:09:07.790 --> 00:09:09.620
on a specific set of devices.

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:11.819
And they'll be a
way to do that too.

00:09:11.819 --> 00:09:13.610
You'll be able to write
custom test scripts

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:16.320
and run them on physical or
virtual devices you choose.

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:18.840
And you can even do that
from Android Studio,

00:09:18.840 --> 00:09:21.310
your other continuous
integration systems.

00:09:24.907 --> 00:09:27.240
Once you have a good sense
that your product is working,

00:09:27.240 --> 00:09:29.320
another great way
to grow reach is

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:32.960
to obviously expand to
other countries, globally.

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:35.210
You'll need to think
about localizing your app

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:37.170
and your Play Store listing.

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:39.140
From within the dev
console, we provide

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:41.140
tools and recommendations
to help you translate

00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:44.020
your app across global markets.

00:09:44.020 --> 00:09:45.380
Take Netflix, for example.

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:49.510
They recently had a lot of press
about globalizing their app.

00:09:49.510 --> 00:09:52.010
And you know, they didn't just
translate their title and app

00:09:52.010 --> 00:09:54.510
description, but also
made sure screenshots

00:09:54.510 --> 00:09:58.260
and video trailers accurately
represented the app

00:09:58.260 --> 00:09:59.038
in all markets.

00:10:03.170 --> 00:10:03.675
Pricing.

00:10:03.675 --> 00:10:05.050
Also an area you
want to consider

00:10:05.050 --> 00:10:07.170
to make sure your
price translates

00:10:07.170 --> 00:10:11.470
for local expectations,
making sure your price doesn't

00:10:11.470 --> 00:10:15.000
look like it's like
$1.73, like here.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:16.590
Or the cultural
equivalent of that,

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:20.310
which differs by country,
what the sort of standards

00:10:20.310 --> 00:10:21.370
are around pricing.

00:10:21.370 --> 00:10:24.350
And so we help you figure
that out automatically.

00:10:24.350 --> 00:10:26.470
For example, we saw 2x lift.

00:10:26.470 --> 00:10:29.960
You can see here in
Japan for those that

00:10:29.960 --> 00:10:31.970
rounded to the nearest yen.

00:10:31.970 --> 00:10:34.254
So this was pretty cool.

00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:39.750
So now that you've heard
more about tactical advice

00:10:39.750 --> 00:10:42.670
on extracting benefits
of reach out of Android,

00:10:42.670 --> 00:10:44.380
let's hear more from
a startup developer

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:46.950
who has been capitalizing on
some of those opportunities.

00:10:46.950 --> 00:10:49.810
WeVideo is a startup right
here in our backyard,

00:10:49.810 --> 00:10:52.290
and has some relevant
experience to share.

